  "prompt": "What are some examples of covalent and ionic bonds?",
  "response": "Here are some examples of covalent and ionic bonds:\n\nCovalent Bonds:\n1. Water (H2O)\n2. Methane (CH4)\n3. Carbon dioxide (CO2)\n4. Oxygen (O2)\n5. Hydrogen chloride (HCl)\n6. Glucose (C6H12O6)\n\nIonic Bonds:\n1. Sodium chloride (NaCl - table salt)\n2. Potassium chloride (KCl)\n3. Calcium carbonate (CaCO3)\n4. Magnesium oxide (MgO)\n5. Sodium fluoride (NaF)\n6. Potassium hydroxide (KOH)\n\nCharacteristics:\nCovalent Bonds:\n- Formed by sharing electrons\n- Typically between non-metal atoms\n- Lower melting and boiling points\n- Often exist as molecules\n\nIonic Bonds:\n- Formed by electron transfer\n- Between a metal and non-metal\n- High melting and boiling points\n- Form crystal lattice structures\n- Conduct electricity when dissolved in water\n\nThese examples illustrate the different ways atoms can bond and form compounds with distinct properties.",
